INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (4, 1, '2013-11-10 18:57:26', '2013-11-10 18:57:26', '<h2>Andrea Ray</h2>\r\n<img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-151" style="margin-left: 25px; margin-right: 25px;" title="Andrea Ray" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Andrea-profileshoot-640-300x200.jpg" alt="Andrea profile" width="300" height="200" />I was introduced to Iyengar Yoga at an early age, about 20 years ago. I have come a long way since and have now been teaching many public classes for the past 8 years. I hold Junior Intermediate Teaching Level 3 qualification.\r\n\r\nMore than just the physical postures, yoga as a philosophy has always fascinated me. I feel very fortunate to have access to the never-ageing wisdom through the work of Patanjali’s Yogasutras and through more recent works of BKS Iyengar that has brought Yoga to the world’s consciousness.\r\n\r\nMy daily practice is focused on finding deeper connection with myself and reconnecting with the core of being. I’ve been fortunate to study under many wise and knowledgeable teachers from all around the world as well as with the Iyengar family.\r\n\r\nTeaching is a great joy. I enjoy teaching students new to yoga and seeing the positive changes it brings. I also enjoy working with experienced students a on much more subtle level to help them find the teacher within them. Dealing with my own obstacles on the path has made me more compassionate and understanding.\r\n\r\nIyengar yoga offers endless variety of approaches and I focus on using the appropriate tools according to the need of students, and the cycle of nature.\r\n\r\nI\'ve recently moved back to London and I\'m currently on maternity leave. I\'ll be looking to teach again in 2015 around West London. In the recent past, I\'ve been teaching in Bristol and around Central and North London.\r\n\r\n<span style="line-height: 1.5;"><span style="line-height: 1.5;">You can also </span><a style="line-height: 1.5;" title="My Iyengar Yoga Profile" href="https://www.iyengaryoga.org.uk/profile/4796" target="_blank">visit my Profile</a><span style="line-height: 1.5;"> on the Iyengar Yoga Association UK website.</span></span>', 'About Me', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'about-me', '', '', '2015-05-30 09:33:56', '2015-05-30 09:33:56', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=4', 4, 'page', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (5, 1, '2013-11-10 18:57:26', '2013-11-10 18:57:26', 'My roots are in Slovakia, where I was born in to a family of teachers, priests and wood guardians. My childhood although very happy, was shaded by the dark veil of dysfunctional communism. The right to believe in true values was replaced by unrealistic vision of uniformed justice. All spiritual teaching and traditions had been lost in the confusion of the time. \r\n\r\nHowever, this also meant I wasn’t put in any religious box and had complete freedom to find my own truths, which lie deep in the heart, and beyond all religions. \r\n\r\nA completely new world opened up for me, when I was introduced to yoga on the innocent side of my teens. The Iyengar tradition travelled through a branch of teachers in Poland over the Tatras to Slovakia. My first experience of it was on a family yoga summer camp organized by the local Yoga association. They promoted the whole lifestyle of vegetarian diet, natural living and, to our amusement, also explored mild techniques of Hatha yoga Kriyas (cleansing) like daily neti (nasal cleansing) and occasional vaman dhauti (stomach cleansing involving vomiting). Combined with the excitement of many new friends I was captivated and started attending weekly class and returned to many more summer camps. \r\n\r\nI moved to London in my early 20’s and soon discovered the Iyengar Institute there. Overwhelmed by the number of local and visiting teachers, I spent several years attending many classes every week as well as all the possible workshops. My home practice became strong and I started attending teacher training. It was a great time of exploration with all my peers, learning from each other, eager to explore the subject of yoga. We learned to teach so we could share it with others. At this time I was saturated with the local teaching, so I started to travel to seek more and in early 2007 I visited India for the first time. In 2008 I was awarded my Iyengar Introductory Teacher Training certificate and started to teach more or less full time.   \r\n\r\nI became completely immersed in the art of teaching and keep learning with each class. Time and experience have been great teachers for me.  \r\n\r\nAt the same time I reached the limits of my physical body and kept dealing with recurring hamstring injuries, unable to progress. My strong enthusiasm shaded over my weak spots and after the initial jumpstart I could not maintain practicing with the same intensity without causing further damage. I stopped attended classes and spent nearly a year focusing on recuperative practice. Towards the end of the period I joined Mira Mehta’s classes. She showed me the silent truth which lies beyond excitement and uncovered the weaknesses in my practice and teaching. Bit by bit the changes have been rippling through my body and I feel more connected and free than ever. \r\n\r\nLove has played a part in my move to Bristol, where I currently live, practice and teach.', 'About Me', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '4-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-10 18:57:26', '2013-11-10 18:57:26', '', 4, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=5', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
