INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (16, 1, '2013-11-10 19:35:05', '2013-11-10 19:35:05', 'Yog Dīksha roughly translates to initiation into Yoga, and is a space for sharing the traditional teachings. The word Yoga may be interpreted in several different ways. It can be understood as \'union\' or to be one with the creation. It can also be thought of as tying together the various inclinations of the mind.\r\n\r\nYoga is an ancient Indian school of thought, that provides a unique point of view into the workings of the world by understanding our own selves better.\r\n\r\nThe word Yoga, however, and especially in the West, has been overused and misused and has come to mean a mere shadow of its original intent. The usage of the word Yog tries to distance itself from what has come to be understood as "Yoga". Both words however, mean the same, and have been used interchangeably throughout the website.\r\n\r\n<i>Explore further: </i><i><a href="Sutras.html">The Yoga Sūtras of Patañjali</a></i><a style="line-height: 1.5;" href="file:///Users/cray/Sites/YogDiksha3/Ashtanga.html"><i>\r\n</i></a>', 'Welcome', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '15-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-10 19:35:05', '2013-11-10 19:35:05', '', 15, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=16', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (17, 1, '2013-11-10 19:41:53', '2013-11-10 19:41:53', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-99" style="border: 10px solid black;" alt="Candles" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_45.png" width="720" height="360" /></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYoga Sūtras of Patañjali is an ancient text written in Sanskrit and considered to be the definitive work outlining the eightfold path of Yoga (Aṣṭānga Yoga). It is believed to be written around 2nd century BC and is a compilation of 196 aphorisms (or sūtras) attributed to sage Patañjali.\r\n\r\nThe Yoga Sūtras are divided into four chapters:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Samādhi Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Sādhana Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Vibhūti Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Kaivalya Pāda</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe succinct nature of the text potent with meaning, does not however disclose its secrets easily. The Sūtras that form the heart of Yoga philosophy disclose a new aspect to the yogi every time they are read and re-read.\r\n\r\nBelow is a brief outline of the chapters.\r\n\r\n<strong>Samādhi Pāda</strong>\r\nThe first chapter, Samādhi Pāda, seems starts out at the final stage of Aṣṭānga Yoga, Samādhi, where the seer and the soul are one. The chapter explains the meaning of Yoga, the aim of Yoga, the paths to follow, and the obstacles on the way.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sādhana Pāda</strong>\r\nThe second chapter, Sādhana Pāda, is about Practice. Practice is the means of attaining the goals described in the first chapter. It identifies the source of afflictions of the mind and the effect of karma. The 8-fold path of Yoga is described herein.\r\n\r\n<strong>Vibhūti Pāda</strong>\r\nThe third chapter, Vibhūti Pāda, talks about the accomplishments or experiences that may be encountered by the yogi on his quest. It warns to not be wavered by the powers one may acquire on the way, and not lose sight of the real objective.\r\nThe fourth and final chapter, Kaivalya Pāda, or Absolute Freedom reached by the yogis whose consciousness is pure and free from the movements of nature. Dharma-meghaḥ samādhi, the fruit of yoga brings the end of afflictions and karma.', 'Yoga Sutras', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'yoga-sutras', '', '', '2014-01-04 17:49:47', '2014-01-04 17:49:47', '', 277, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=17', 2, 'page', '', 0); 
