INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (54, 1, '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '<i>Āsana</i> (आसन) is yoga posture. It\'s such a posture, where the whole body works together. There is harmony and union in-between all the parts of the body as well as all the layers (koshas). The mind is ever-present but still and one-pointed.\r\n\r\nStiffness and dullness is replaced by poise and serenity.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nस्थिरसुखमासनम्॥४६॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.46 : Sthira Suhka Āsanam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>yoga postures implies steadiness and ease</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•sthira = steady, stable, motionless</li>\r\n	<li>•sukham = comfortable, ease filled</li>\r\n	<li>•asanam = meditation posture</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nप्रयत्नशैथिल्यानन्त्यसमापत्तिभ्याम्॥४७॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.47: Prayatna Śaithilya Ananta Samāpattibhyām </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this only happens once the effort to maintain the posture lessens and one surrenders to the infinite one  </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•prayatna = effort, endeavor</li>\r\n	<li>•shaithilya = by relaxing, loosening, lessening, slackening</li>\r\n	<li>•ananta = infinite, endlessness</li>\r\n	<li>•samapattibhyam = by focusing attention on, by coalescence, coincidence, merging</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nततो द्वन्द्वानभिघातः॥४८॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.48: Tatah Dvandvāh Anabhighātah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>then one becomes impartial to the opposing sensations like pleasure and pain, heat and cold, honour and dishonour</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•dvandva = opposites, dualities</li>\r\n	<li>•anabhighata = cessation of disturbance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhen the mind is still, the Self can be felt.\r\n\r\nBy understanding the true meaning of yog; union, the path is clear and the obstacles become visible. By using our bodies and the various Asanas with understanding, we are able to remove these obstacles, and start pursuing the yogic path. Due to the modern lifestyle, we are often completely removed from nature. Our bodies are imbalanced, and the natural intelligence of the body is well hidden behind the stiffness and unconsciousness. It takes a long time to reverse the process and reestablish the lost balance. One should be aware of this obstacle and not to confuse the achievement of Asana for a goal of Yoga. Once the balance is restored, Asana becomes a gate for deep exploration of the Breath and Life force (Prana), Senses(Indria), Mind(Manas), Individual Soul (Atman) and the Universal Soul (Brahman, Ananda) . The next stages of Ashtanga yoga guide us through.\r\n\r\nFrom this point the achievement of Asana is just the beginning of the pursuit, rather than the end.', 'Āsana', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'asana', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=54', 3, 'page', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (55, 1, '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '<i>Āsana</i> (आसन) is yoga posture. It\'s such a posture, where the whole body works together. There is harmony and union in-between all the parts of the body as well as all the layers (koshas). The mind is ever-present but still and one-pointed.\r\n\r\nStiffness and dullness is replaced by poise and serenity.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></a>\r\n\r\nस्थिरसुखमासनम्॥४६॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.46 : Sthira Suhka Āsanam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>yoga postures implies steadiness and ease</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•sthira = steady, stable, motionless</li>\r\n	<li>•sukham = comfortable, ease filled</li>\r\n	<li>•asanam = meditation posture</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nप्रयत्नशैथिल्यानन्त्यसमापत्तिभ्याम्॥४७॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.47: Prayatna Śaithilya Ananta Samāpattibhyām </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this only happens once the effort to maintain the posture lessens and one surrenders to the infinite one  </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•prayatna = effort, endeavor</li>\r\n	<li>•shaithilya = by relaxing, loosening, lessening, slackening</li>\r\n	<li>•ananta = infinite, endlessness</li>\r\n	<li>•samapattibhyam = by focusing attention on, by coalescence, coincidence, merging</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nततो द्वन्द्वानभिघातः॥४८॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.48: Tatah Dvandvāh Anabhighātah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>then one becomes impartial to the opposing sensations like pleasure and pain, heat and cold, honour and dishonour</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•dvandva = opposites, dualities</li>\r\n	<li>•anabhighata = cessation of disturbance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhen the mind is still, the Self can be felt.\r\n\r\nBy understanding the true meaning of yog; union, the path is clear and the obstacles become visible. By using our bodies and the various Asanas with understanding, we are able to remove these obstacles, and start pursuing the yogic path. Due to the modern lifestyle, we are often completely removed from nature. Our bodies are imbalanced, and the natural intelligence of the body is well hidden behind the stiffness and unconsciousness. It takes a long time to reverse the process and reestablish the lost balance. One should be aware of this obstacle and not to confuse the achievement of Asana for a goal of Yoga. Once the balance is restored, Asana becomes a gate for deep exploration of the Breath and Life force (Prana), Senses(Indria), Mind(Manas), Individual Soul (Atman) and the Universal Soul (Brahman, Ananda) . The next stages of Ashtanga yoga guide us through.\r\n\r\nFrom this point the achievement of Asana is just the beginning of the pursuit, rather than the end.', 'Āsana', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '54-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '', 54, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=55', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (56, 1, '2013-11-10 20:58:33', '2013-11-10 20:58:33', '<i>Prānāyāma</i> (प्राणायाम), is the practice of the control of the flow of energy in the body. It is done using techniques of extension and retention of the breathe. The life force (prana) is freed to flow through out the body and vitality, health and stability are invited with this practice.\r\n\r\nSteady practice of Asanas is inevitable base for Pranayama practice.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nतस्मिन् सति श्वासप्रश्वासयोर्गतिविच्छेदः प्राणायामः॥४९॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.49: Tasmin Satiśvāsa Praśvāsayoh Gativicchedah Prānāyāmah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the next step is Pranayama, regulation of inhalation and exhalation with retention</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tasmin = upon that (perfection of Asana)</li>\r\n	<li>•sati = being accomplished</li>\r\n	<li>•shvasa = inhalation</li>\r\n	<li>•prashvsayoh = exhalation</li>\r\n	<li>•gati = movements</li>\r\n	<li>•vichchhedah = cessation, interruption</li>\r\n	<li>•pranayamah = expansion of prana (life force) through regulation of breath</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nबाह्याभ्यन्तरस्तम्भवृत्तिर्देशकालसंख्याभिः परिदृष्टो दीर्घसूक्ष्मः॥५०॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.50: Bāhya abhyantara stambha vrittiḥ deśa kāla sankhyābhih paridriṣṭaḥ dīrgha sūkṣmaḥ</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the three movements; prolonged and subtle exhalation, inhalation and retention of breath, are regulated by positioning, timing and number of cycles of breath </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>•abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>•stambha = holding, restraint, suspension, retention, cessation</li>\r\n	<li>•vrittih = movements, fluctuations</li>\r\n	<li>•desha = place, spot, space, location</li>\r\n	<li>•kala = time, period, duration</li>\r\n	<li>•sankhyabhih = by these three, number, count of</li>\r\n	<li>•paridrishtah = regulated by, observed by</li>\r\n	<li>•dirgha = made long, prolonged, slow</li>\r\n	<li>•sukshmah = and subtle, fine</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nबाह्याभ्यन्तरविषयाक्षेपी चतुर्थः॥५१॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.51: Bāhya abhyantara viśaya akṣepi chaturthaḥ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>beyond this is the froth method of breathing, which surpasses the internal and external realms of breath </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>•abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>•vishaya = region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>•akshepi = going beyond, surpassing, setting aside</li>\r\n	<li>•chaturthah = the fourth</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nततः क्षीयते प्रकाशावरणम्॥५२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.52: Tataḥ kśīyate prakaśa āvaranam </b>\r\n\r\n<i>than the veil covering the illumination vanishes </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, thence, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•kshiyate = is destroyed, thinned, diminishes, vanishes</li>\r\n	<li>•prakasha = light, illumination</li>\r\n	<li>•avaranam = veil, covering<i>\r\n</i></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nPranayama is the highest discipline on the yogic path. The most powerful tool of <b><i>practice</i></b> (Abhyasa) to allow the next four stages to happen through letting go or <b><i>renunciation</i></b> (Vairagya).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe initiation of this practice is done by experienced teacher to avoid damage to the nervous system which can be caused by incorrect and inappropriate use of the techniques.', 'Prānāyāma', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'pranayama', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=56', 4, 'page', '', 0); 
