INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (100, 1, '2013-11-12 00:14:56', '2013-11-12 00:14:56', '<a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_45.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-99" alt="Candles" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_45.png" width="985" height="379" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>The Yoga Sūtras</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Yoga Sūtras of Patañjali is a ancient text written in Sanskrit and considered as the definitive work outlining the eightfold path of Yoga (Aṣṭānga Yoga). It is believed to be written around 2nd century BC and is a compilation of 196 aphorisms (or sūtras) attributed to sage Patañjali.\r\n\r\nThe Yoga Sūtras are divided into four chapters:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Samādhi Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Sādhana Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Vibhūti Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Kaivalya Pāda</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe succinct nature of the text potent with meaning, does not however disclose its secrets easily. The Sūtras that form the heart of Yoga philosophy disclose a new aspect to the yogi every time they are read and re-read.\r\n\r\nBelow is a brief outline of the chapters.\r\n\r\n<strong>Samādhi Pāda</strong>\r\nThe first chapter, Samādhi Pāda, seems starts out at the final stage of Aṣṭānga Yoga, Samādhi, where the seer and the soul are one. The chapter explains the meaning of Yoga, the aim of Yoga, the paths to follow, and the obstacles on the way.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sādhana Pāda</strong>\r\nThe second chapter, Sādhana Pāda, is about Practice. Practice is the means of attaining the goals described in the first chapter. It identifies the source of afflictions of the mind and the effect of karma. The 8-fold path of Yoga is described herein.\r\n\r\n<strong>Vibhūti Pāda</strong>\r\nThe third chapter, Vibhūti Pāda, talks about the accomplishments or experiences that may be encountered by the yogi on his quest. It warns to not be wavered by the powers one may acquire on the way, and not lose sight of the real objective.\r\nThe fourth and final chapter, Kaivalya Pāda, or Absolute Freedom reached by the yogis whose consciousness is pure and free from the movements of nature. Dharma-meghaḥ samādhi, the fruit of yoga brings the end of afflictions and karma.', 'Yoga Sutras', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:14:56', '2013-11-12 00:14:56', '', 17, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=100', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (101, 1, '2013-11-12 00:15:23', '2013-11-12 00:15:23', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nयोगाङ्गाऽनुष्ठानादशुद्धिक्षये ज्ञानदीप्तिराविवेकख्यातेः॥२८॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.28: Yoga </b><b>anga anuṣṭhanad aśuddhi kśaye jñana dīptih a viveka khyāteḥ</b>\r\n\r\n<i>through the practice of the different limbs of yoga the impurities are eliminated and the light of the eternal wisdom is free to shine </i>\r\n\r\nयमनियमासनप्राणायामप्रत्याहारधारणाध्यानसमाधयोऽष्टावङ्गानि॥२९॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.29: yama niyama āsana prānāyāma pratyāhāra dhāranā dhyāna samādhi aṣtau angani</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the eight limbs of yoga are: Yama, Niyama, Asana, Pranayama, Pratyahara, </i>\r\n\r\n<i>Dharana, Dhyana and Samadhi</i>\r\n\r\nThe second chapter of the Yoga Sūtras (<i>Sādhana Pāda</i>) defines Yoga as made up of eight parts (Āṣṭanga). The eight limbs of Yoga describe the different facets of the Yogic practice and gives us direction on the path.\r\n\r\nThe stages go from gross to subtle, and from outwards to inwards. There is a gradual ascent from one state to the next, however, the states often overlap, and we can catch glimpses of one in the other.', 'Eight Limbs of Yoga', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '41-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:15:23', '2013-11-12 00:15:23', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=101', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (102, 1, '2013-11-12 00:16:04', '2013-11-12 00:16:04', '<i>Yama</i> (यम) is the the first step in the eightfold path of Yoga.\r\n\r\nIt refers to the universal moral principles that are ingrained in all humans. They are simple to understand, as we naturally relate to these ethics. However, to follow them steadfastly in thought, word and deed may present a challenge to even the most dedicated of yogis.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a style="color: #ea9629; text-decoration: underline; outline: #000000;" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nThe five principles of Yama are:\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Ahiṃsā</i></b><i> : </i><i>non-violence</i>\r\n\r\nअहिंसाप्रतिष्ठायां तत्सन्निधौ वैरत्यागः॥३५॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.35: Ahimsa Pratiṣthāyām tat sannidhau vairatyāgah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>when non-violence is firmly rooted, hostility ceases in ones presence</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Satya </i></b><i>: truth</i>\r\n\r\nसत्यप्रतिष्ठायां क्रियाफलाश्रयत्वम्॥३६॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.36: Satya Pratiṣṭhāyām Kriyā Phala Āśhrayatvam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>with truth firmly rooted, one attains the result of action without acting</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Asteya</i></b><i> : non-stealing</i>\r\n\r\nअस्तेयप्रतिष्ठायां सर्वरत्नोपस्थानम्॥३७॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.37: Asteya pratiṣṭhāyām sarva ratna upasthānam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>as non-stealing is firmly rooted, all the jewels and treasures will be available to one </i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Brahmaćarya</i></b><i> : continence</i>\r\n\r\nब्रह्मचर्यप्रतिष्ठायां<i> वीर्यलाभः॥३८॥</i>\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.38: Brahmacharya pratiṣṭhāyām vīrya lābhah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>with firmly rooted continence a great strength and vitality is acquired </i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b><i>Aparigraha </i></b><i>: non-possession</i>\r\n\r\nअपरिग्रहस्थैर्ये जन्मकथंतासंबोधः॥३९॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.39: Aparigraha sthairye janma kathānta sambodhah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>knowledge of past and future lives unfolds as one is freed from greed for possessions</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Yama', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '48-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:16:04', '2013-11-12 00:16:04', '', 48, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=102', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (103, 1, '2013-11-12 00:16:24', '2013-11-12 00:16:24', '<i>Niyama</i> (नियम) means moral discipline for the individual. It forms the second rung of Aṣṭānga yoga. <i>Niyama</i> relates to us at the individual level as opposed to <i>Yama </i>that is at a social level.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nThe five <i>Niyama </i>are:\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Saucha :</i></b><i> Cleanliness</i>\r\n\r\nशौचात् स्वाङ्गजुगुप्सा परैरसंसर्गः॥४०॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.40: Sauchat sva-anga jugupsa paraiḥ asaṃsargaḥ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>through cleanliness and purity of body and mind one will become impartial towards one\'s own body and bodies of others </i>\r\n\r\nसत्त्वशुद्धिसौमनस्यैकाग्र्येन्द्रियजयात्मदर्शनयोग्यत्वानि<i> च॥४१॥</i>\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.41: Sattva śuddhi saumanasya ekāgra indriya-jaya ātma darśana yogyatvāni cha </b>\r\n\r\n<i>with the body and mind cleansed, the senses will be under control, the mind will be content and prepared to experience the inward endeavor</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Santośa :</i></b><i> Contentment</i>\r\n\r\nसंतोषादनुत्तमसुखलाभः॥४२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.42: Santoṣa anuttamah sukha lābhah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>contentment brings supreme happiness</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Tapas :</i></b><i> Penance</i>\r\n\r\nकायेन्द्रियसिद्धिरशुद्धिक्षयात्तपसः॥४३॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.43: Kāyā Indriya siddhiḥ aśuddhi kśayāt tapasah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>austerity destroys impurity and brings mastery over the body, senses and mind</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>            </i><b><i>Svādhyāya :</i></b><i> Self-study</i>\r\n\r\nस्वाध्यायादिष्टदेवतासंप्रयोगः॥४४॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.44:  Svādhyāyāt ishta samprayogah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>from self-study and reflection on sacred words, one attains contact and communion  with that underlying natural reality </i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>        </i><b><i>Īśvara Praṇidhāna :</i></b><i> Faith</i>\r\n\r\nसमाधिसिद्धिरीश्वरप्रणिधानात्॥४५॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.45: Samādhi siddhiḥ īshvarapranidhāna</b>\r\n\r\n<i>from an attitude of letting go into one\'s source, the illuminate state of perfect concentration called Samadhi is attained</i>', 'Niyama', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:16:24', '2013-11-12 00:16:24', '', 52, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=103', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (104, 1, '2013-11-12 00:17:04', '2013-11-12 00:17:04', '<i>Āsana</i> (आसन) is yoga posture. It\'s such a posture, where the whole body works together. There is harmony and union in-between all the parts of the body as well as all the layers (koshas). The mind is ever-present but still and one-pointed.\r\n\r\nStiffness and dullness is replaced by poise and serenity.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nस्थिरसुखमासनम्॥४६॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.46 : Sthira Suhka Āsanam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>yoga postures implies steadiness and ease</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•sthira = steady, stable, motionless</li>\r\n	<li>•sukham = comfortable, ease filled</li>\r\n	<li>•asanam = meditation posture</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nप्रयत्नशैथिल्यानन्त्यसमापत्तिभ्याम्॥४७॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.47: Prayatna Śaithilya Ananta Samāpattibhyām </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this only happens once the effort to maintain the posture lessens and one surrenders to the infinite one  </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•prayatna = effort, endeavor</li>\r\n	<li>•shaithilya = by relaxing, loosening, lessening, slackening</li>\r\n	<li>•ananta = infinite, endlessness</li>\r\n	<li>•samapattibhyam = by focusing attention on, by coalescence, coincidence, merging</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nततो द्वन्द्वानभिघातः॥४८॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.48: Tatah Dvandvāh Anabhighātah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>then one becomes impartial to the opposing sensations like pleasure and pain, heat and cold, honour and dishonour</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•dvandva = opposites, dualities</li>\r\n	<li>•anabhighata = cessation of disturbance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhen the mind is still, the Self can be felt.\r\n\r\nBy understanding the true meaning of yog; union, the path is clear and the obstacles become visible. By using our bodies and the various Asanas with understanding, we are able to remove these obstacles, and start pursuing the yogic path. Due to the modern lifestyle, we are often completely removed from nature. Our bodies are imbalanced, and the natural intelligence of the body is well hidden behind the stiffness and unconsciousness. It takes a long time to reverse the process and reestablish the lost balance. One should be aware of this obstacle and not to confuse the achievement of Asana for a goal of Yoga. Once the balance is restored, Asana becomes a gate for deep exploration of the Breath and Life force (Prana), Senses(Indria), Mind(Manas), Individual Soul (Atman) and the Universal Soul (Brahman, Ananda) . The next stages of Ashtanga yoga guide us through.\r\n\r\nFrom this point the achievement of Asana is just the beginning of the pursuit, rather than the end.', 'Āsana', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '54-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:17:04', '2013-11-12 00:17:04', '', 54, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=104', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (105, 1, '2013-11-12 00:17:27', '2013-11-12 00:17:27', '<i>Prānāyāma</i> (प्राणायाम), is the practice of the control of the flow of energy in the body. It is done using techniques of extension and retention of the breathe. The life force (prana) is freed to flow through out the body and vitality, health and stability are invited with this practice.\r\n\r\nSteady practice of Asanas is inevitable base for Pranayama practice.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nतस्मिन् सति श्वासप्रश्वासयोर्गतिविच्छेदः प्राणायामः॥४९॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.49: Tasmin Satiśvāsa Praśvāsayoh Gativicchedah Prānāyāmah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the next step is Pranayama, regulation of inhalation and exhalation with retention</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tasmin = upon that (perfection of Asana)</li>\r\n	<li>•sati = being accomplished</li>\r\n	<li>•shvasa = inhalation</li>\r\n	<li>•prashvsayoh = exhalation</li>\r\n	<li>•gati = movements</li>\r\n	<li>•vichchhedah = cessation, interruption</li>\r\n	<li>•pranayamah = expansion of prana (life force) through regulation of breath</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nबाह्याभ्यन्तरस्तम्भवृत्तिर्देशकालसंख्याभिः परिदृष्टो दीर्घसूक्ष्मः॥५०॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.50: Bāhya abhyantara stambha vrittiḥ deśa kāla sankhyābhih paridriṣṭaḥ dīrgha sūkṣmaḥ</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the three movements; prolonged and subtle exhalation, inhalation and retention of breath, are regulated by positioning, timing and number of cycles of breath </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>•abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>•stambha = holding, restraint, suspension, retention, cessation</li>\r\n	<li>•vrittih = movements, fluctuations</li>\r\n	<li>•desha = place, spot, space, location</li>\r\n	<li>•kala = time, period, duration</li>\r\n	<li>•sankhyabhih = by these three, number, count of</li>\r\n	<li>•paridrishtah = regulated by, observed by</li>\r\n	<li>•dirgha = made long, prolonged, slow</li>\r\n	<li>•sukshmah = and subtle, fine</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nबाह्याभ्यन्तरविषयाक्षेपी चतुर्थः॥५१॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.51: Bāhya abhyantara viśaya akṣepi chaturthaḥ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>beyond this is the froth method of breathing, which surpasses the internal and external realms of breath </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>•abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>•vishaya = region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>•akshepi = going beyond, surpassing, setting aside</li>\r\n	<li>•chaturthah = the fourth</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nततः क्षीयते प्रकाशावरणम्॥५२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.52: Tataḥ kśīyate prakaśa āvaranam </b>\r\n\r\n<i>than the veil covering the illumination vanishes </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, thence, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•kshiyate = is destroyed, thinned, diminishes, vanishes</li>\r\n	<li>•prakasha = light, illumination</li>\r\n	<li>•avaranam = veil, covering<i>\r\n</i></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nPranayama is the highest discipline on the yogic path. The most powerful tool of <b><i>practice</i></b> (Abhyasa) to allow the next four stages to happen through letting go or <b><i>renunciation</i></b> (Vairagya).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe initiation of this practice is done by experienced teacher to avoid damage to the nervous system which can be caused by incorrect and inappropriate use of the techniques.', 'Prānāyāma', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '56-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:17:27', '2013-11-12 00:17:27', '', 56, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=105', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (106, 1, '2013-11-12 00:17:51', '2013-11-12 00:17:51', '<i>Pratyāhāra</i> (प्रत्याहार) is withdrawal of the senses. The presence of this state of mind is inevitable for further persuasion inside.\r\n\r\nThe senses are our gateways to the outer world. They constantly receive input from nature and convey it to the mind. The mind is drawn automatically towards these experiences and tends to fluctuate from one thing to another.\r\n\r\nWith the body freed by Asanas and the mind stilled by Pranayama, the senses are more easily withdrawn in to Pratyāhāra.\r\n\r\nThen the ever-active surroundings do not automatically transform into fluctuations of the mind and one is able to explore the inner world.\r\n\r\nThis stillness allows us to follow up the strong attraction inwards to explore the Source of all existence.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nस्वविषयासंप्रयोगे चित्तस्य स्वरूपानुकार इवेन्द्रियाणां प्रत्याहारः॥५४॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.54: Sva viśaya asamprayoge cittasya svarupe anukāraḥ iva indriyāṇam pratyāhāraḥ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>prayahara is the restoration of senses to the original purity of mind, by renouncing external objects</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•sva = their own</li>\r\n	<li>•vishaya = objects, region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>•asamprayoge = not coming into contact with, cessation of engagement</li>\r\n	<li>•chittasya = of the mind field</li>\r\n	<li>•svarupe = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>•anukarah = imitate, resemble, follow, be engaged with</li>\r\n	<li>•iva = like, as though, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>•indriyanam = mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n	<li>•pratyaharah = withdrawal of the indriyas (the senses), bringing inward</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nततः परमा वश्यतेन्द्रियाणाम्॥५५॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.55: Tatah parama vaśyata indriyaṇam </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this leads to the absolute control of the sense organs</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•parama = highest, supreme, ultimate, perfected</li>\r\n	<li>•vashyata = mastery, control, being willed</li>\r\n	<li>•indriyanam = of the mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Pratyāhāra', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:17:51', '2013-11-12 00:17:51', '', 60, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=106', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (107, 1, '2013-11-12 00:18:11', '2013-11-12 00:18:11', '<i>Dhāranā</i> (धारणा) is another involutionary stage of yoga. Literally it means concentration. In this state the mind is intensely focussed in one-pointed concentration.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nधारणासु च योग्यता मनसः॥५३॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.53: Dhāranāsu Ća Yogyatā Manasah </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the fourth Pranayama prepares the mind for concentration</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•dharanasu = for concentration, for dharana</li>\r\n	<li>•cha = and</li>\r\n	<li>•yogyata = fitness, preparedness, qualification, capability</li>\r\n	<li>•manasah = mind</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nदेशबन्धश्चित्तस्य धारणा॥१॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.1: Deśah bandhah cittasya dhāranā </b>\r\n\r\n<i>attention fixed upon one point is Dhāranā; concentration  </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•deshah = place, object, point, spot</li>\r\n	<li>•bandhah = binding to, holding, fixing, uniting</li>\r\n	<li>•chittasya = of the mind, consciousness</li>\r\n	<li>•dharana = concentration, focusing, directing attention</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Dhāranā', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '58-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:18:11', '2013-11-12 00:18:11', '', 58, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=107', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (108, 1, '2013-11-12 00:18:32', '2013-11-12 00:18:32', '<i>Dhyāna</i> (ध्यान) or meditation is a blissful state of mind where one\'s consciousness is absorbed in the essence of the object of contemplation. This state is a result of dedicated practice of the previous (especially involutionary) stages.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nतत्र प्रत्ययैकतानता ध्यानम्॥२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.2: Tatra Pratyaya Ekatānatā Dhyānam  </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the union of mind and the object is Dyana; meditation</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatra = there, therein (in that place or desha of 3.1)</li>\r\n	<li>•pratyaya = the cause, the feeling, causal or cognitive principle, notion, content of mind, presented idea, cognition</li>\r\n	<li>•ekatanata = one continuous flow of uninterrupted attention (eka = one; tanata = continued directedness)</li>\r\n	<li>•dhyanam = meditation</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Dhyāna', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:18:32', '2013-11-12 00:18:32', '', 62, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=108', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (109, 1, '2013-11-12 00:18:58', '2013-11-12 00:18:58', '<i>Samādhi</i> (समाधि) is the final stage of the path of Yoga. It may be roughly translated as liberation. Through constant practice of meditation, the mind unites with the source of creation.\r\n\r\nThe individual soul (<i>ātman</i>) fuses with the cosmic consciousness (<i>brahman</i>)\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" /></a></p>\r\nतदेवार्थमात्रनिर्भासं स्वरूपशून्यमिव समाधिः॥३॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.3: Tadeva Arthamātranirbhāsam Svarūpaśūnyam Iva Samādhih  </b>\r\n\r\n<i>when only the essence of the object shines forth in the mind, as if devoid of it\'s own form, </i>\r\n\r\n<i>that state of deep absorption is Samadhi. </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tad = that</li>\r\n	<li>•eva = the same</li>\r\n	<li>•artha = object, place, point</li>\r\n	<li>•matra = only, alone</li>\r\n	<li>•nirbhasam = shines forth, appears</li>\r\n	<li>•svarupa = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>•shunyam = devoid of, empty</li>\r\n	<li>•iva = as if, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>•samadhih = meditation in its higher state, deep absorption of meditation, the state of perfected concentration, spiritual absorption</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Samādhi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '64-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-12 00:18:58', '2013-11-12 00:18:58', '', 64, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=109', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (113, 2, '2013-11-14 21:56:53', '2013-11-14 21:56:53', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_41.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-38" alt="Stick figure Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_41.png" /></a></p>\n\n<h3>Bristol City Yoga</h3>\n<em><a href="http://www.bristolcityyoga.co.uk/">www.bristolcityyoga.co.uk</a></em>\n\n<b style="line-height: 1.5;">Monday</b><span style="line-height: 1.5;">          9.15 - 10.15am          General</span>\n\n<hr style="height: 2px; width: 500px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; border-color: #CCCCCC; color: #ffffff;" noshade="noshade" size="2" width="500" />\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3><span style="line-height: 1.3;">Bath Iyengar Yoga Centre</span></h3>\n<em><a style="line-height: 1.5;" href="http://www.bath-iyengar-yoga.com/">www.bath-iyengar-yoga.com</a></em>\n\n<b>Tuesday </b>         7 - 8.30pm                Beginners*\n\n<hr noshade="noshade" size="2" width="500" />\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Bristol Buddhist Centre</h3>\n<em><a href="http://www.bristol-buddhist-centre.org/">www.bristol-buddhist-centre.org</a></em>\n\n<b>Wednesday</b>    5.45 - 7.15pm            Beginners\n\n<b>Thursday</b>        5.45 - 7.15pm            General\n\n<hr noshade="noshade" size="2" width="500" />\n\n<h3></h3>\n<h3>Yogawest</h3>\n<em><a href="http://www.yogawest.co.uk/">www.yogawest.co.uk</a></em>\n\n<b>Friday  </b>           12.30 - 2pm               General\n\n<b>Friday </b>             6 - 7.30pm                Restorative\n\n<b>Sunday </b>          11.45 - 1.15pm          Intermediate\n\n<hr noshade="noshade" size="2" width="500" />\n\n<b><i>Level guidance</i></b>\n\n<b>Beginners and General</b>\n\nThese classes are suitable for all levels from newcomers to improvers.\n\nAll basic asanas (yoga postures) are being taught with emphases on Standing postures and Shoulder Stand to create firm foundation. Breath observation and relaxation are being taught.\n\n* Please note that Bath Iyengar yoga centre requires students to attend their foundation course or have similar Iyengar yoga experience before enrolling for the Level 1 class.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Intermediate</b>\n\nThis class is for students whose practice is strong enough to be introduced to Headstand and beyond. Focus is given to understand from within the principles of the body, breath and mind. Students are encouraged to built their home practice.\n\n<b>Restorative</b>\n\nThis class teaches and explores supported practice. This type of practice is inevitable in time of weakness and fatigue. It also gives us space to explore more subtle aspects of yoga practice; the breath and the mind.', 'Classes', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '37-autosave-v1', '', '', '2013-11-14 21:56:53', '2013-11-14 21:56:53', '', 37, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/37-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
