INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (129, 1, '2013-11-16 16:21:33', '2013-11-16 16:21:33', '<a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_45.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-99" alt="Candles" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_45.png" width="985" height="379" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYoga Sūtras of Patañjali is an ancient text written in Sanskrit and considered to be the definitive work outlining the eightfold path of Yoga (Aṣṭānga Yoga). It is believed to be written around 2nd century BC and is a compilation of 196 aphorisms (or sūtras) attributed to sage Patañjali.\r\n\r\nThe Yoga Sūtras are divided into four chapters:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Samādhi Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Sādhana Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Vibhūti Pāda</li>\r\n	<li>Kaivalya Pāda</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe succinct nature of the text potent with meaning, does not however disclose its secrets easily. The Sūtras that form the heart of Yoga philosophy disclose a new aspect to the yogi every time they are read and re-read.\r\n\r\nBelow is a brief outline of the chapters.\r\n\r\n<strong>Samādhi Pāda</strong>\r\nThe first chapter, Samādhi Pāda, seems starts out at the final stage of Aṣṭānga Yoga, Samādhi, where the seer and the soul are one. The chapter explains the meaning of Yoga, the aim of Yoga, the paths to follow, and the obstacles on the way.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sādhana Pāda</strong>\r\nThe second chapter, Sādhana Pāda, is about Practice. Practice is the means of attaining the goals described in the first chapter. It identifies the source of afflictions of the mind and the effect of karma. The 8-fold path of Yoga is described herein.\r\n\r\n<strong>Vibhūti Pāda</strong>\r\nThe third chapter, Vibhūti Pāda, talks about the accomplishments or experiences that may be encountered by the yogi on his quest. It warns to not be wavered by the powers one may acquire on the way, and not lose sight of the real objective.\r\nThe fourth and final chapter, Kaivalya Pāda, or Absolute Freedom reached by the yogis whose consciousness is pure and free from the movements of nature. Dharma-meghaḥ samādhi, the fruit of yoga brings the end of afflictions and karma.', 'Yoga Sutras', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-16 16:21:33', '2013-11-16 16:21:33', '', 17, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
