INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (148, 1, '2013-11-18 23:13:43', '2013-11-18 23:13:43', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" title="Tree of Yoga" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></a></p>\r\nयोगाङ्गाऽनुष्ठानादशुद्धिक्षये ज्ञानदीप्तिराविवेकख्यातेः॥२८॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.28: Yoga </b><b>anga anuṣṭhanad aśuddhi kśaye jñana dīptih a viveka khyāteḥ</b>\r\n\r\n<i>through the practice of the different limbs of yoga the impurities are eliminated and the light of the eternal wisdom is free to shine </i>\r\n\r\nयमनियमासनप्राणायामप्रत्याहारधारणाध्यानसमाधयोऽष्टावङ्गानि॥२९॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.29: yama niyama āsana prānāyāma pratyāhāra dhāranā dhyāna samādhi aṣtau angani</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the eight limbs of yoga are: <a title="Yama" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/yama/">Yama</a>, <a title="Niyama" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/niyama/">Niyama</a>, <a title="Āsana" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/asana/">Asana</a>, <a title="Prānāyāma" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/pranayama/">Pranayama</a>, <a title="Pratyāhāra" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/pratyahara/">Pratyahara</a>, </i>\r\n\r\n<i><a title="Dhāranā" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/dharana/">Dharana</a>, <a title="Dhyāna" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/dhyana/">Dhyana</a> and <a title="Samādhi" href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/yoga-sutras/eight-limbs-of-yoga/samadhi/">Samadhi</a></i>\r\n\r\nThe second chapter of the Yoga Sūtras (<i>Sādhana Pāda</i>) defines Yoga as made up of eight parts (Āṣṭanga). The eight limbs of Yoga describe the different facets of the Yogic practice and gives us direction on the path.\r\n\r\nThe stages go from gross to subtle, and from outwards to inwards. There is a gradual ascent from one state to the next, however, the states often overlap, and we can catch glimpses of one in the other.', 'Eight Limbs of Yoga', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '41-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-18 23:13:43', '2013-11-18 23:13:43', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/41-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wpydnv_posts` VALUES (150, 2, '2013-11-26 07:47:34', '2013-11-26 07:47:34', '<h2>Andrea Ray</h2>\n<a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Andrea-profileshoot-640.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-151" alt="Andrea profile" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Andrea-profileshoot-640-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200" /></a>I was introduced to Iyengar Yoga at an early age, about 20 years ago. I have come a long way since and have now been teaching many public classes for the past 8 years. I hold Junior Intermediate Teaching Level 3 qualification.\n\nMore than just the physical postures, yoga as a philosophy has always fascinated me. I feel very fortunate to have access to the never-ageing wisdom through the work of Patanjali’s Yogasutras and through more recent works of BKS Iyengar that has brought Yoga to the world’s consciousness.\n\nMy daily practice is focused on finding deeper connection with myself and reconnecting with the core of being. I’ve been fortunate to study under many wise and knowledgeable teachers from all around the world as well as with the Iyengar family.\n\nTeaching is a great joy. I enjoy teaching students new to yoga and seeing the positive changes it brings. I also enjoy working with experienced students a on much more subtle level to help them find the teacher within them. Dealing with my own obstacles on the path has made me more compassionate and understanding.\n\nIyengar yoga offers endless variety of approaches and I focus on using the appropriate tools according to the need of students, and the cycle of nature.\n\nI currently practice, live and teach in Bristol.\n\n<span style="line-height: 1.5;"><span style="line-height: 1.5;">You can also </span><a style="line-height: 1.5;" title="My Iyengar Yoga Profile" href="https://www.iyengaryoga.org.uk/profile/4796" target="_blank">visit my Profile</a><span style="line-height: 1.5;"> on the Iyengar Yoga Association UK website.</span></span>', 'About Me', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '4-autosave-v1', '', '', '2013-11-26 07:47:34', '2013-11-26 07:47:34', '', 4, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/4-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
